Loading and cleaning data:

otoliths_data <- read.csv("incrmement measurements.csv") |>
  clean_names()

#selecting wanted data from area "ETAS".
otolith_selected_data <- otoliths_data |>
  dplyr::select(area, fish_id, sex, age, increment) |>
  na.omit(otolith_selected_data) |> 
  filter(area == "ETAS", age > 1)

# Although there are no occurances of NA in data, including code in line 36 is 
# arguably good practice, in case NA-occurance in future data.

Testing different models:

# 1 as random effect. This is the control. 
mod <- lmer(increment ~ log(age) + sex + log(age) * sex + (1 | fish_id),
            data = otolith_selected_data)

#age as random effect:
mod_rand_age <- lmer(increment ~ log(age) + sex + log(age) * sex + (log(age) | fish_id),
                     data = otolith_selected_data)
summary(mod_rand_age)

#mod_rand_age has the lowest AIC = -10935 and is, 
# out of the three models this model having log(age) as the random effect, 
#most fit for proper representation of the data in the model.

Model diagnosis and sampling data

# Augmenting data
aug_data <- augment(mod_rand_age)


sample_oto_data <- aug_data[sample(nrow(aug_data), size = 600), ] #sample for publishable plot
small_sample_oto_data <-  aug_data[sample(nrow(aug_data), size = 50), ] #sample for diagnostic boxplot


# Using check_model() from perfomance package. I am still experiencing problems with the package, 
# even after the updates from assignment 4.
# It will only show the output in the rendered HTML-file and not in my editor, which makes it hard to work with. 
# Will therefore be using the other diagnostic plots instead. 
check_model(mod_rand_age) 

### box-plots of residuals by fish_id (small sample). 
ggplot(small_sample_oto_data, aes(x = fish_id, y = .resid)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  coord_flip()

# standardized residuals versus fitted values
ggplot(aug_data, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + 
  geom_point(colour = "blue") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) 

# qq-plot of residuals:  
qqmath(mod_rand_age) # acceptable between x = -2.2 and 1.8, but still quite a few

# deviations from the linear slope.

#qqplot of random effects: 
qqmath(ranef(mod_rand_age))
$fish_id

Comment on the model:

Due to the spread of the data shown by the tests done for diagnosis of the model, the conclusion is that the model is not quite as fitting or good for this data set as we would ideally want. We see that there is a non-linear spread in the dataset with this model, so in a future re-do we should use a different model.

Making a plot

plot_model <- sample_oto_data |> 
 ggplot(aes(x = `log(age)`, y = increment, colour = sex)) +
 geom_jitter(aes(alpha = 0.4)) +
 geom_line(aes(group = fish_id), size = 0.2, alpha = 0.4) +
 geom_line(aes(y = .fixed), size = 1.3) +
 theme_bw() +
 labs(x = "Age (years)",
     y = "Increment") +
 theme(plot.caption = element_text(size = 12),
      axis.text = element_text(size = 10)) +
 scale_color_viridis_d() + #using this for colour blinds
 guides(alpha=FALSE)

Making a table

#converting to a tidy tibble using tidy():

model_tidy <- tidy(mod_rand_age) 

#Initialize a variable 'model_filtered' with the 'model_tidy' tibble filtered to only include 
#rows where the 'term' column matches any of the following values: 
# "(Intercept)", "log(age)", "sexM", "log(age):sexM":

model_filtered <- model_tidy[
  model_tidy$term %in% c("(Intercept)", "log(age)", "sexM", "log(age):sexM"), 
  ]


#1. Initialize a variable 'gt_table' with the function 'gt' applied to 'model_filtered'
#2. Pipe the 'gt_table' into the function 'cols_hide' with the argument 'columns' set to "group"
#3. Renaming columns for a better and more presentable finish. 
# Values in gt_tabel are from the model "mod_rand_age".

gt_table <- gt(model_filtered) |>
 cols_hide(columns = "group") |> 
 cols_label( effect = "Effect", 
            term = "Term", 
            estimate = "Estimate", 
            std.error = "Std.error", 
            df = "Degrees of Freedom",
            statistic = "T-value") |> 
 fmt_number(decimals = 3)

gt_table <- gt_table |> 
 tab_header(
   title = md("Fixed effect values")
 )
# Print the gt table
gt_table

### Importing packages:

```{r}
#| label: loading packages
#| output: false
library(dplyr)
library(janitor)
library(lme4)
library(lmerTest)
library(ggplot2)
library(broom.mixed)
library(multcomp)
library(performance)
library(see)
library(lattice)
library(broom.mixed)
library(gt)

```

### Loading and cleaning data:

```{r}
#| label: loading & selecting data
#| output: false
otoliths_data <- read.csv("incrmement measurements.csv") |>
  clean_names()

#selecting wanted data from area "ETAS".
otolith_selected_data <- otoliths_data |>
  dplyr::select(area, fish_id, sex, age, increment) |>
  na.omit(otolith_selected_data) |> 
  filter(area == "ETAS", age > 1)

# Although there are no occurances of NA in data, including code in line 36 is 
# arguably good practice, in case NA-occurance in future data. 
```

### Testing different models:

```{r}
#| label: testing models with different randon slopes

# 1 as random effect. This is the control. 
mod <- lmer(increment ~ log(age) + sex + log(age) * sex + (1 | fish_id),
            data = otolith_selected_data)

#age as random effect:
mod_rand_age <- lmer(increment ~ log(age) + sex + log(age) * sex + (log(age) | fish_id),
                     data = otolith_selected_data)
summary(mod_rand_age)

#sex as random effect:
mod_rand_sex <- lmer(increment ~ log(age) + sex + log(age) * sex + (sex | fish_id),
                     data = otolith_selected_data)

anova(mod, mod_rand_age, mod_rand_sex) 


#mod_rand_age has the lowest AIC = -10935 and is, 
# out of the three models this model having log(age) as the random effect, 
#most fit for proper representation of the data in the model. 
```

### Model diagnosis and sampling data

```{r}
#| label: model diagnosis, and sample-data


# Augmenting data
aug_data <- augment(mod_rand_age)


sample_oto_data <- aug_data[sample(nrow(aug_data), size = 600), ] #sample for publishable plot
small_sample_oto_data <-  aug_data[sample(nrow(aug_data), size = 50), ] #sample for diagnostic boxplot


# Using check_model() from perfomance package. I am still experiencing problems with the package, 
# even after the updates from assignment 4.
# It will only show the output in the rendered HTML-file and not in my editor, which makes it hard to work with. 
# Will therefore be using the other diagnostic plots instead. 
check_model(mod_rand_age) 

### box-plots of residuals by fish_id (small sample). 
ggplot(small_sample_oto_data, aes(x = fish_id, y = .resid)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  coord_flip()

# standardized residuals versus fitted values
ggplot(aug_data, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + 
  geom_point(colour = "blue") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) 

# qq-plot of residuals:  
qqmath(mod_rand_age) # acceptable between x = -2.2 and 1.8, but still quite a few
# deviations from the linear slope.

#qqplot of random effects: 
qqmath(ranef(mod_rand_age))

```

### Comment on the model:

Due to the spread of the data shown by the tests done for diagnosis of the model, the conclusion is that the model is not quite as fitting or good for this data set as we would ideally want. We see that there is a non-linear spread in the dataset with this model, so in a future re-do we should use a different model.

### Making a plot

```{r}
#| label: publishable plot
#| fig-cap: "Figure 1: Plot showing differences and trends increments of otolith rings in male and female fish."


plot_model <- sample_oto_data |> 
 ggplot(aes(x = `log(age)`, y = increment, colour = sex)) +
 geom_jitter(aes(alpha = 0.4)) +
 geom_line(aes(group = fish_id), size = 0.2, alpha = 0.4) +
 geom_line(aes(y = .fixed), size = 1.3) +
 theme_bw() +
 labs(x = "Age (years)",
     y = "Increment") +
 theme(plot.caption = element_text(size = 12),
      axis.text = element_text(size = 10)) +
 scale_color_viridis_d() + #using this for colour blinds
 guides(alpha=FALSE)

plot_model



```

```{r}
#| label: Making a table using gt()
#| tbl-cap: "Table 1: Table showing the models fixed effects and their uncertainties"


#converting to a tidy tibble using tidy():

model_tidy <- tidy(mod_rand_age) 

#Initialize a variable 'model_filtered' with the 'model_tidy' tibble filtered to only include 
#rows where the 'term' column matches any of the following values: 
# "(Intercept)", "log(age)", "sexM", "log(age):sexM":

model_filtered <- model_tidy[
  model_tidy$term %in% c("(Intercept)", "log(age)", "sexM", "log(age):sexM"), 
  ]


#1. Initialize a variable 'gt_table' with the function 'gt' applied to 'model_filtered'
#2. Pipe the 'gt_table' into the function 'cols_hide' with the argument 'columns' set to "group"
#3. Renaming columns for a better and more presentable finish. 
# Values in gt_tabel are from the model "mod_rand_age".

gt_table <- gt(model_filtered) |>
 cols_hide(columns = "group") |> 
 cols_label( effect = "Effect", 
            term = "Term", 
            estimate = "Estimate", 
            std.error = "Std.error", 
            df = "Degrees of Freedom",
            statistic = "T-value") |> 
 fmt_number(decimals = 3)

gt_table <- gt_table |> 
 tab_header(
   title = md("Fixed effect values")
 )
```
